{
  "doc_id": "26162",
  "text": "Hyaluronan (HA) 2 is a connective tissue glycosaminoglycan, which in vivo is present as a high molecular mass component of extracellular matrices. It is synthesized by three mammalian HA synthase isoenzymes (HAS1, HAS2, and HAS3), and its breakdown is mediated by the hyaluronidase (Hyal) group of enzymes. HA regulates cellular processes through interaction with cell-surface receptors (principally CD44) and has been implicated in numerous biological processes, including embryonic development, wound healing, chronic inflammation, and tumor progression [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Therefore, HA has an important role in maintaining tissue homeostasis.",
